Fig. 5
 provides a comparison between experimental and theoretical curves derived from different mechanism models. Upon evaluation of the theoretical curves in N2 and CO2 atmospheres, it was observed that the experimental curve exhibited a correlation with D4 and A2 models, respectively (Table 4
). The Ea was calculated to be 282.01 and 123.20 kJ mol−1 in 2 atm with R2 of 0.982 and 0.976, respectively. These results were in good agreement with those obtained using the FWO method. In accordace with the four-dimensional diffusion model, diffusion effects were the predominant factor within the solid reaction. As the reaction proceeded, a product layer formed around the particles, resulting in a reduction in the rate of product formation rate due to the expansion of the product layer. The expression g(α) = 1-(2/3)α-(1-α)2/3 was found to be an appropriate model for separator decomposition in an N2 atmosphere. Singh et al. [45], Ling and Li [46] similarly indicated that the co-pyrolysis of PE with biomass could be described by the D4 mechanism. In contrast, the Avrami-Erofeev nucleation mechanism may have occurred as a consequence of the coking reaction, resulting in the formation of char. Furthermore, Sun et al. [47] proposed that the "hot" char stage of in-situ gasification in a CO2 atmosphere followed the A2 model. The expression g(α)=(-ln(1-α))1/2 may prove an effective description of the decomposition process in a CO2 atmosphere.
